sentences: Charles Edward "Rusty" York (May 24, 1935 – January 26, 2014) was an American musician and singer, and member of the Rockabilly Hall of Fame.
Early years =
York listened to the Grand Ole Opry on Saturday nights and to the Mid-Day Merry-Go-Round and Cas Walker programs from Knoxville radio.
A 1951 concert appearance by Earl Scruggs and the Foggy Mountain Boys inspired him.
In 1952, York's family moved to the Over-the-Rhine area of Cincinnati, Ohio.
Within a few weeks, his father died, and York took a kitchen job at Walt's Restaurant.
York began playing in local clubs with Wilson Spivey during the evenings.
They soon started playing more mostly rock-and-roll songs, but would still perform about 15 minutes of bluegrass nightly.
By 1958, York had assembled a band, the Cajuns, which consisted of York on vocals and guitar, Bill Lanham on bass, saxophone player Jimmy Risch, John Bower on piano, and Rick Lundy on drums.
In 1959, the group backed Jackie Shannon (later known as Jackie DeShannon) on "Just Another Lie".
In 1959, they also recorded "Just Another Lie", also for Fraternity.
Later in 1959, Pat Nelson rented the King studio for an independent session intended for his PJ label.
In 1959, "Sugaree" reached No. 77 on the Billboard Hot 100.
Later years ==
By the 1960s, York had returned to bluegrass and turned towards country music.
In 1961, he started building a studio in his garage.
By the early 1970s, York had retired from performing to concentrate on his Jewel Records imprint/studio full-time.
Jewel continued to operate out of Cincinnati throughout the 1980s and 1990s, and into the 21st century.

After selling the Jewel Recording Studio in 2008, York and his family moved to Florida.
York died on January 26, 2014, in Redington Shores, Florida, after a long bout with degenerative brain disease.
